04018nam a22005655i 9780226346656DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263466567 a10.7208/97802263466562doi  a(DE-B1597)523588  a(OCoLC)941137700  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBH39 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a302.2311 aJagoda, Patrick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNetwork Aesthetics /cPatrick Jagoda. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b27 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Network Aesthetics -- t1. Maximal Aesthetics: Network Novels -- t2. Emergent Aesthetics: Network Films -- t3. Realist Aesthetics: Televisual Networks -- t4. Participatory Aesthetics: Network Games -- t5. Improvisational Aesthetics: Alternate Reality Games -- tCoda: After Networks (Comes Ambivalence) -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe term "network" is now applied to everything from the Internet to terrorist-cell systems. But the word's ubiquity has also made it a cliché, a concept at once recognizable yet hard to explain. Network Aesthetics, in exploring how popular culture mediates our experience with interconnected life, reveals the network's role as a way for people to construct and manage their world-and their view of themselves. Each chapter considers how popular media and artistic forms make sense of decentralized network metaphors and infrastructures. Patrick Jagoda first examines narratives from the 1990s and 2000s, including the novel Underworld, the film Syriana, and the television series The Wire, all of which play with network forms to promote reflection on domestic crisis and imperial decline in contemporary America. Jagoda then looks at digital media that are interactive, nonlinear, and dependent on connected audiences to show how recent approaches, such as those in the videogame Journey, open up space for participatory and improvisational thought. Contributing to fields as diverse as literary criticism, digital studies, media theory, and American studies, Network Aesthetics brilliantly demonstrates that, in today's world, networks are something that can not only be known, but also felt, inhabited, and, crucially, transformed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAesthetics. 0aArtsxPhilosophy. 0aCognitive science. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226346656423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226346656.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles